      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hmm, we might want to be careful about this. I\u0027m sure we have code that indiscriminately sends whatever error it gets back to the client. In this case, that would send them the contents of what could be a corrupted JWT JSON.\n\nProbably better to just mention metadataname and/or filename. If we really want body, logging is better, although it\u0027s not a great idea to log sensitive data either.",
      "revId": "10411354f46539b3298e42727b4f5c89d961f265",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "01bb0599_bb3aabfb",
        "filename": "go/auth/auth.go",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 373,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-13T15:15:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If we have code that sends whatever error it has back to the client, *that* is the problem. It means we are vulnerable to an XSS reflection bug.\n\nI believe we have a helper, httpsutils.ReportError that does not do that.\n\nAlso, if we are authenticating somehow (i.e. calling this function) in an http.Handler - IMO *that* is a bug; we should only authenticate when the server boots up.\n\nI would imagine that 99% of the time we have an error, we log an unexpected response given to us from metadata/ (which is helpful) and \u003c 1% of the time, we would log a corrupted JWT JSON (which, I agree, is potentially sensitive).\n\nI would like this error to help in the 99% of cases rather than be opaque 100% of the time.",
      "parentUuid": "3d9f8729_7350ce4d",
      "revId": "10411354f46539b3298e42727b4f5c89d961f265",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
